TP3 : Logistic regression¶

The purpose of this tutorial is to implement and use the Logistic Regression for binary classification. We will apply this method to the problem of handwritten characters to learn how to distinguish two numbers (here 5 and 6).

1. Logistic regression, IRLS algorithm.¶

Preliminary question: the algorithm¶

Have a look at the function regression_logistique.m and locate the main steps of the algorithm you have been taught (see course).¶

You can comment the code in the cell below.

In [2]:
def regression_logistique(X,t,Nitermax=20,eps_conv=1e-3):
    '''Entrees :
    X = [ones(N_train,1) x_train];
    t = class_train 
    Nitermax = nombre maximale d'itérations (20 par défaut)
    eps_conv = critère de convergence sur norm(w-w_old)/norm(w) ; 
    eps_conv=1e-3 par défaut
    
    Sorties : 
    w : vecteur des coefficients de régression logistique
   Niter : nombre d'itérations utilisées effectivement
   
   Fonction de régression logistique pour la classification binaire.
   
   Utilisation :
       Nitermax = 50
       eps_conv = 1e-4
       [w,Niter] = regression_logistique(X,t,Nitermax,eps_conv)
    '''
    N_train = X.shape[0]

    #initialisation : 1 pas de l'algorithme IRLS
    w = np.zeros((X.shape[1],))
    w_old = w 
    y = 1/2*np.ones((N_train,))
    R = np.diag(y*(1-y))   # diag(y_n(1-y_n))
    z = X.dot(w_old)-la.inv(R).dot(y-t)
    w = la.inv(X.T.dot(R).dot(X)).dot(X.T).dot(R).dot(z)

    # boucle appliquant l'algorithme de Newton-Raphson
    Niter = 1
    while ( (la.norm(w-w_old)/la.norm(w)>eps_conv) & (Niter<Nitermax) ):
        Niter = Niter+1
        y = 1/(1+np.exp(-X.dot(w)))
        R = np.diag(y*(1-y))  
        w_old = w 
        z = X.dot(w_old)-la.inv(R).dot(y-t) 
        w = la.inv(X.T.dot(R).dot(X)).dot(X.T).dot(R).dot(z)
         
    return w, Niter

Exercise 1 : the logistic function of decision¶

  1. Use the function regression_logistique.m to estimate the logistic regression vector w. Indication : use Nitermax = 50; eps_conv=1e-3;.
  2. Compute the decision function $f(x) = argmax_k P(C_k|x)$ on the test set to get the classification results. Recall that $y_n=\sigma(w^T x)$ (logistic function) and that using vectors you may directly write $y=\sigma(Xw)$, with the column of ones in X.
  3. Display the results by plotting the points from both the training set and the test set.
  4. Write the equation which defines the decision boundary.
  5. Artificially add a few points to the training set far from the decision boundary to check the robustness of logistic regression to outliers. Check the behaviour of LDA for comparison in this case and comment.

5.2. Checking robustness of LDA in presence of outliers¶

In [17]:
# Indices of features belonging to each class (0,1)
indiceC1_train = np.nonzero(t_train_outliers.ravel()==1)
indiceC0_train = np.nonzero(t_train_outliers.ravel()==0)

# Features split as per class
X_C1_train=x_train_outliers[indiceC1_train].T # Features of class 1
X_C0_train=x_train_outliers[indiceC0_train].T # Features of class 0

# Number of features per class
N1_train = np.size(X_C1_train,axis=1) # Number of features of class 1
N0_train = np.size(X_C0_train,axis=1) # Number of features of class 0
In [18]:
# LDA Maximum likelihood estimates computation
# Estimation of weights pi_1 and pi_2 for each class
pi_1 = N1_train/N_train_outliers # For class 1
pi_0 = N0_train/N_train_outliers # For class 0

# Estimation of empirical means mu_1 and mu_2 for each class
mu_1 = (X_C1_train.sum(1))/N1_train # Same as "mu_1 = X1_train.mean(1)"
mu_0 = (X_C0_train.sum(1))/N0_train # Same as "mu_2 = X2_train.mean(1)"

mu_1=mu_1.reshape(2,1)
mu_0=mu_0.reshape(2,1)


# Estimation of empirical covariance matrices sigma_1 and sigma_2
sigma_1 = ((X_C1_train - mu_1).dot((X_C1_train - mu_1).T))/N1_train # The same as "sigma_1 = np.cov(X1_train.T, ddof=0)"
# sigma_1 = (np.matmul((X_C1_train-mu_1),(X_C1_train-mu_1).T))/N1_train
sigma_0 = ((X_C0_train - mu_0).dot((X_C0_train - mu_0).T))/N0_train # The same as "sigma_2 = np.cov(X2_train.T, ddof=0)"

# sigma_2 = (np.matmul((X_C2_train-mu_2),(X_C2_train-mu_2).T))/N2_train

# Computation of the common averaged covariance sigma (average of intra-class covariances)
sigma = (N1_train*sigma_1 + N0_train*sigma_0)/N_train_outliers
In [19]:
# Computation of log-probabilities of belonging to each class
# We keep only dependance on the classes 1 and 2
log_proba_1 = mu_1.T.dot(inv(sigma)).dot(X_C1_train) - (1/2)*mu_1.T.dot(inv(sigma)).dot(mu_1) + log(pi_1)
log_proba_0 = mu_0.T.dot(inv(sigma)).dot(X_C0_train) - (1/2)*mu_0.T.dot(inv(sigma)).dot(mu_0) + log(pi_0)

# Decision of classification
# Linear parameters for the decision function 1
w1 = inv(sigma).dot(mu_1)
w01 = - (1/2)*mu_1.T.dot(inv(sigma)).dot(mu_1) + log(pi_1)

# Linear parameters for the decision function 2
w2 = inv(sigma).dot(mu_0)
w02 = - (1/2)*mu_0.T.dot(inv(sigma)).dot(mu_0) + log(pi_0)

5.3. Comparison and Comments¶

In [23]:
# Test Error of LOGISTIC REGRESSION
# Decision of classification using Logistic Regression
predictions = np.where(1/(1+np.exp(-X_test.dot(w)))> 0.5, 1, 0)

error_Log_Reg = 1-mean(t_test == predictions)
print("The test error of logistic regression taking into account the outliers is", error_Log_Reg)

# Test Error of LDA
# We compute the hyperplanes for seperation of regions between classes
f_X_1 = w1.T.dot(x_test.T) + w01
f_X_2 = w2.T.dot(x_test.T) + w02

# Decision of classification using LDA
decision_vector = np.where(f_X_1.T > f_X_2.T, 1, 0)


error_LDA = 1-mean(t_test == decision_vector)
print("The test error of LDA taking into account the outliers is", error_LDA)


"""
We can notice that the test error using logistic regression is much lower than the one using LDA.
When, in the presence of outliers, the test error of logistic regression is 7%, the one of LDA is 35%
Therfore, from the above results, we can say that logistic regression is robust in presence of outliers,
however, LDA is not robust to outliers.
"""

The test error of logistic regression taking into account the outliers is 0.06999999999999995
The test error of LDA taking into account the outliers is 0.3537

Separating the training and test sets¶

We keep in the training set the 145 first images of 5s and the 200 first images of 6s:

In [27]:
''' 

1. Concatenate images of 5 and 6.
2. Generate array of 1s to put label in all observations.
3. Now put 0 in the label of all 145 first observations, beloinging to the images of number 5.
4. We end up with a separete array for the x's and the labels. x_train_brut that contains observations of the images of both numbers 5 and 6,
and class_train that contains their respective labels 0 and 1.

'''
x_train_brut = np.vstack((train_5[:145,:], train_6[:200,:]))
N_train = np.size(x_train_brut,axis=0)
class_train = np.ones((345,1))   # label 1 for digit 6
class_train[:145] = 0       # label 0 for digit 5

x_test_brut = np.vstack((train_5[145:,:], train_6[200:,:]))
N_test = np.size(train_5,axis=0)+np.size(train_6,axis=0)-N_train
class_test = np.ones((N_test,1))   # label 1 for digit 6
class_test[:(556-145)] = 0       # label 0 for digit 5

# The predictions using the implemented regression_logistique function
Nitermax = 50; eps_conv=1e-3;
X_train = np.hstack((np.ones((np.size(synth_train[:,1:],axis=0),1)),synth_train[:,1:]));
X_test = np.hstack((np.ones((np.size(synth_test[:,1:],axis=0),1)),synth_test[:,1:]));

# w, Niter = regression_logistique(X, t)
[w_logit,Niter] = regression_logistique(X_train,t,Nitermax,eps_conv)

y_hat_test_1 = np.where(1/(1+np.exp(-X_test.dot(w_logit)))> 0.5, 1, 0)


# The predictions using SK-learn
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
clf = LogisticRegression()
clf.fit(synth_train[:,1:], t)

y_hat_test_2 = clf.predict(synth_test[:,1:])


# Test error
error_1 = 1-mean(t_test == y_hat_test_1)
print("The test error of logistic regression manually implemented is", error_1)

error_2 = 1-mean(t_test == y_hat_test_2)
print("The test error of SK-learn logistic regression is", error_2)

The test error of logistic regression manually implemented is 0.06000000000000005
The test error of SK-learn logistic regression is 0.06000000000000005

Conclusion: The function "regression_logistique" implemented has the same performance as the one of SK-learn in terms of test error, using synthetic data.¶

In [47]:
# The predictions using SK-learn
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
clf = LogisticRegression(tol=1e-3,C=1e100,solver='newton-cholesky',max_iter=13)
"""
Newton-Cholesky solver is combining the Newton-Raphson optimization algorithm (Iterated Reweighted Least Squares algorithm)
with the Cholesky matrix decomposition in order to approximate numerically the solution of the logistic regression optimization
problem to find an estimate of the parameter w.

Note that C = 1/lambda, where lambda is the regularization parameter added to the cost function of logistic regression.
Therefore, to minimize the effect of regularization, C has to be to very high, knowing that it's default value is 1.
"""
clf.fit(x_train, class_train.ravel())

y_hat_test_4 = clf.predict(x_test) # Predictions


# Test error
error_4 = 1-np.mean(class_test.ravel() == y_hat_test_4)
print("The test error of SK-learn logistic regression is", error_4)

The test error of SK-learn logistic regression is 0.07657142857142862

Comments : Using handwritten digits data, the logistic regression implemented in SK-learn seems to be more robust, because of the regularization which is applied by default. Although we decreased the effect of this regularization by increase the factor C (the inverse of the regularization parameter) up to 10^100 (which means that the regularization parameter is 10^-100, close to zero), it effect is not completed removed.¶

Knowing that the aim of regularization is to avoid overfitting, it is not a surprise that SK-learn algorithm performs slightly better than the regression_logistique function implemented.¶
